<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-07-11T22:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-07-11T22:00:00-05:00" n="227" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d227">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/13603: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Canton</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Spiker</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Canton</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-07-12T11:00:00+08:00">July 12, 1936—11
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received 8:35 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Referring to my telegram of July 9, 4 p.m.<note n="65" xml:id="d227fn65">Not printed.</note> Marshals Chen, Pai and other leading military
                            and civil members of Southwest Political Council yesterday addressed
                            telegram to second plenary session at Nanking urging adoption of the
                            five point program proposed by Southwest June 22. (See my telegram of
                            June 23, noon, and June 29, 4 p.m.) Situation here remains quiet.</p>
                        <p>2. Sent to the Department, Peiping, Nanking, Shanghai and Hankow.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Spiker</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>